	<text id="material" x="37" y="65" width="675" height="346" autosize="" style="WIZARD_TEXT" visible="true" fx="SHOW" hidefx="HIDE" scroll="AUTO">
		<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Topic&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;One of your roles is to help caregivers understand how to best support children's healthy development.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Let's look at a situation in which a caregiver has concerns about a child’s development.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Scenario &lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;My 2 ½-year-old grandson ignores my rule about not touching the glass decorations on the coffee table. I've reminded him at least three times about the rule, but he still reaches for the glass decorations. What should I do?&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Question&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;How would you respond to this caregiver?&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Sample Feedback&lt;/B&gt; &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Toddlers are active explorers and need to have a place where they can explore freely. You should find a specific play area where the child can safely explore everything or consider putting your glass collection out of reach when your grandchild is at your house.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
	</text>
